          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex> (the topological space consisting of a single point).
    We see that, for a sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (X_n,F^n)]]></fr:tex> are the components of a cosimplicial set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
    The functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex> (of global sections) is the functor

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2171</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.1.13.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.1.13.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.1.13.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \Gamma \colon  F^\bullet          \mapsto  \operatorname {Ker}\big (           \Gamma (X_0,F^0)           \rightrightarrows  \Gamma (X_1,F^1)         \big ).       \tag{5.1.13.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is a complex of abelian sheaves, we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)]]></fr:tex> the chain complex whose components are the cosimplicial abelian groups <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K^n)]]></fr:tex>, and by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s} \Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)]]></fr:tex> the associated simple complex.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
